3) Weaknesses / risks that feel non-senior-commensurate

These are the issues Iâ€™d challenge or re-paper for proper senior credit:

A) Value-leakage to taxes/CarCo ahead of seniors
	â€¢	CarCo pre-waterfall pays taxes and CarCo fees first (daily) before pushing funds up. At Issuer level, Senior Reserve can also be applied to cover CarCo tax shortfalls under certain priorities.
Why it matters: youâ€™re structurally underwriting state/tax seniority plus operating overhead before your own interest, and you may even backfill those with Issuer-level liquidity.
Fix: hard cap & definitions for which CarCo taxes/fees can be funded from Issuer/Reserves; require sweep-first then tax (except VAT held in a dedicated trust account) or ring-fenced tax pre-fund sized and locked; prohibit using Senior Reserve for CarCo obligations other than strictly defined issuer-priority items.

B) Contamination from Non-Eligible Vehicles
	â€¢	The mechanics allow proceeds of Junior and sales of Non-Eligible Vehicles to be recycled into purchasing more Non-Eligible Vehicles during business-as-usual.
Why it matters: that inventory sits outside your borrowing base, yet operational cash commingles until waterfall; in stress, you may be effectively funding working capital cycles you donâ€™t have collateral cover for.
Fix: prohibit any use of cash from the pledged platform to acquire Non-Eligible; or require (i) hard segregation of those flows in off-platform accounts, (ii) independent reporting & daily reconciliations, and (iii) immediate mandatory prepayment of Senior/Mezz from any Non-Eligible sale proceeds.

C) Commingling & control gap at CarCo
	â€¢	Funds sit and are applied daily by CarCo; senior relies on timely sweeps to Issuer and correct waterfall application.
Why it matters: operational failure or distress at CarCo turns into timing and diversion risk for seniors.
Fix: shift to issuer-controlled lockbox (bank-level standing instructions), daily auto-sweep to Issuer accounts with no CarCo discretion, and trust declarations where law allows; add hard commingling reserve sized to max sweep lag Ã— stressed daily sales.

D) Senior liquidity used for non-credit seniorities
	â€¢	Senior/Mezz Reserve application language is broad; in shortfalls they can cover issuer fees/taxes first, not just Senior interest.
Why it matters: transforms liquidity reserve into a quasi-general cash plug, diluting its purpose (timely senior coupons).
Fix: narrow the draw conditions: reserve may fund only (i) Senior note interest, (ii) swap net, (iii) senior trustee/agent feesâ€”not CarCo taxes or other op-line items. If tax coverage is essential, set a separate tax buffer with its own triggers.

E) Ageing & FX frictions in â€œReservedâ€ inventory
	â€¢	â€œReservedâ€ (sold/pending settlement) vehicles can sit 30 days (EUR/SEK) or 5 days (other FX) before re-classifying; operationally you can get FX/settlement slippage and age creep that erodes net realisable value while still counted near-base.
Why it matters: in a falling RV market, every extra day hurts; FX settlement mismatches can spill into liquidity.
Fix: tighten Reserved ageing caps (e.g., 10 business days across the board unless fully hedged); require FX hedging for non-EUR/SEK flows or impose advance-rate haircuts by currency; add a basis/FX liquidity add-on to reserve sizing.

F) Audit scope is strongâ€”but sampling does not solve valuation
	â€¢	The operating audit validates existence/attributes (VIN, country, purchase date, days in stock, etc.) with big samples and 99%/1% confidenceâ€”great for integrity. It does not independently validate fair value/mark-to-market per unit.
Why it matters: your risk is realisation value, not just existence.
Fix: add independent price-check (e.g., monthly third-party guide vs booked costs) and a dynamic valuation haircut table by segment/age; trigger early-am or mandatory prepay if valuation dispersion > threshold.

G) Governance tilt when Senior is amortised
	â€¢	Majority control flips from Senior to Mezz once Senior is repaid; standard in theory, but here operational levers (eligibility exceptions, audit remediation, waivers) can materially alter risk for the tail of Senior.
Why it matters: late-life seniors (or rolling taps) can be impacted by decisions they no longer control.
Fix: embed non-waivable senior protections (eligibility, reserve sizing, commingling, early-am tests) that survive until all senior obligations (including indemnities) are discharged; add senior consent for any waiver affecting reserves/eligibility/BB math.

H) Reliance on related-party mezz/junior
	â€¢	Mezz and Junior are group-held, aligning interests most of the time but creating behavioural risk in stress (e.g., pushing for flexibility that preserves operating capacity over senior de-risking).
Fix: hard-code no-leakage while any PDL/shortfall exists; no junior/mezz distributions if Senior tests < target; enhance independent calculation agent oversight.

I) Italy carve-out transition risk
	â€¢	Re-papering and releasing Italian notes/pledges shifts perimeter. During transition, thereâ€™s operational slippage risk and temporary governance ambiguity.
Fix: require CPs/CSs: (i) simultaneous security release/attach steps are completed and evidenced, (ii) borrowing base tools exclude Italy until fully stood up, (iii) interim utilisation cap until post-transfer audit clean.

â¸»

4) Senior-friendly re-papering asks (practical)
	1.	Cash control & leakage
	â€¢	Daily auto-sweep to issuer; issuer-controlled accounts; no CarCo discretion.
	â€¢	Ban use of any platform cash for Non-Eligible purchases; segregate flows.
	â€¢	Tighten reserve purposes (Senior LR only funds Senior interest/swap/agents).
	2.	Eligibility & valuation
	â€¢	Add market-value test per unit (third-party guide or model) with dynamic haircuts.
	â€¢	Shorten ageing caps (e.g., 210â€“240 days) with escalating haircut grid.
	â€¢	Reserved vehicle limits: cap days across all currencies; hedge FX or haircut.
	3.	Triggers & deleveraging
	â€¢	Add commingling trigger (sweep delay >1 day â†’ early-am).
	â€¢	Introduce inventory-age trigger (e.g., %>180d or >270d) and price-slippage trigger (guide vs book).
	â€¢	Mandatory prepay from (i) Non-Eligible sales and (ii) inventory overage.
	4.	Governance
	â€¢	Senior consent for any changes to BB math, reserves, eligibility, waterfall, or audit scope.
	â€¢	Independent valuation agent mandate; rights to spot-check and increase haircuts.
	5.	Reporting
	â€¢	Daily file: inventory ladder by age/country/currency; sales pipeline; realised gross-to-net per unit; reconciliation to bank statements.
	â€¢	Monthly: roll-rates, realisation histogram vs cost, FX P&L, audit exception log & cure status.

â¸»

5) Bottom line (senior stance)
	â€¢	The platform has good bones (advance-rate discipline, reserve scaffolding, early-am switches, beefed-up audits).
	â€¢	But three items are not senior-commensurate without change:
