Letâ€™s unpack it precisely in securitisation terms, and why itâ€™s not senior-commensurate even though â€œissuer senior feesâ€ normally sit above interest.

â¸»

1ï¸âƒ£ What is normal in a securitisation waterfall

In a true-sale securitisation, you have:
	â€¢	Issuer-level taxes, trustee, agent and servicing fees ranking senior to note interest â€” this is standard and rating-agency-driven.
	â€¢	These are transaction expenses, incurred by the SPV/issuer, and are tightly defined and capped (e.g. â€œSenior Expensesâ€ or â€œIssuer Senior Costsâ€).
	â€¢	Crucially, they are not operating expenses of the originator/servicer, nor any third-party tax liabilities of the seller.

That hierarchy is fine because investors understand they are paying to keep the structure functioning (administration, trustees, hedge, etc.) â€” not subsidising the operating company.

â¸»

2ï¸âƒ£ Whatâ€™s happening in the Auto1 Inventory Facility

Here, the priority of payments at the CarCo level reads:

â€œFirst, to unpaid Taxes due and payable by CarCo â€¦
Second, to CarCo Agent Fees â€¦
Fourth, amounts to be transferred to the Issuer â€¦â€   ï¿¼

That means:
	â€¢	The waterfall pays CarCoâ€™s own taxes (VAT, trade tax, corporate-level obligations) and its internal agent fees before remitting anything to the Issuer.
	â€¢	The Issuer waterfall then begins with its own senior expenses and senior interest.

So, effectively, thereâ€™s a double layer of seniority â€” but the top layer benefits CarCo as operating borrower, not the SPV or noteholders.

â¸»

3ï¸âƒ£ Why this is non-senior-commensurate
	â€¢	These CarCo taxes are not issuer or trust-level taxes; theyâ€™re corporate liabilities of the borrower.
	â€¢	They rank structurally senior to the lenderâ€™s (Issuerâ€™s) claims on collections â€” even though, economically, they belong beneath debt service.
	â€¢	Worse, if CarCoâ€™s cash is tight, those taxes can consume liquidity that should flow up to pay Senior Note interest.
	â€¢	The structure even allows Issuer reserves (Trade-Tax Reserve or Senior Reserve) to be used to backfill those CarCo tax payments  ï¿¼ â€” meaning senior liquidity can be diverted to a borrowerâ€™s statutory obligations.

Thatâ€™s a fundamental inversion of the securitisation principle:
the cash waterfall should serve the funding structure first, not the borrowerâ€™s ongoing business overheads.

â¸»

4ï¸âƒ£ Why itâ€™s not just semantics

Rating agencies tolerate â€œIssuer Senior Expensesâ€ because theyâ€™re predictable and ring-fenced.
Here, CarCoâ€™s taxes are variable, operational, and outside the structureâ€™s control â€” a leakage risk, not a structural necessity.
If CarCo under-remits VAT or faces a tax dispute, the waterfall forces noteholder cash to cure that first, turning the lender into an involuntary tax guarantor.

â¸»

5ï¸âƒ£ How to fix it (what a senior lender would demand)
	â€¢	Reclassify CarCo taxes and agent fees as CarCo Operating Costs, subordinate to any payment to the Issuer (i.e. below debt service).
	â€¢	Retain only issuer-related costs (trustee, agent, account bank, rating, hedge, etc.) in the senior expense bucket.
	â€¢	If tax pre-funding is required for VAT, create a dedicated VAT Reserve funded day-one, segregated and sized to expected obligations, with clear top-up logic â€” not waterfall priority.
	â€¢	Prohibit use of Senior or Trade-Tax Reserve for any borrower-level tax items.

â¸»

âœ… In short:
